repository.label: Repository:
repository.corpname: Southwest Collection/Special Collections Library, Texas Tech University

bioghist.head: Biographical Sketch
bioghist.p: The West Texas Chamber of Commerce had its beginning in Fort Worth, Texas, in December, 1918. This organization was established to effectively serve West Texas through economic and promotional growth with the Texas Chamber of Commerce. It's original office time was located at Abilene, Texas. The records of the Chamber represents its history and operation for the past fifty years. Today the Chamber is a part of the Texas Chamber of Commerce, which merged in 1986 and whose main office is in Austin, Texas.
The Handbook of Texas has published a more in-depth online biography of the West Texas Chamber of Commerce at http://www.tsha.utexas.edu/handbook/online/search.html

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Records of this collection deal with legislative reports from Texas Senate and House bills, constitutional reports, to appropriations and legislation activities. Further, the General Office files detail activities with the West Texas Chamber of Commerce (WTCC) Agriculture Committee, board of directors meetings, bylaw discussions, commodity development, nation wide Chamber of Commerce meetings, correspondence, finance and membership, education, industrial development, labor legislation, workshops, membership, national affairs, new releases, Nomination Committee work, pollution redistricting, rural development, speech material, state affairs, research, Texas Tech University, tourist development, transportation, This is West Texas publication, Washington reception, vocational activities, water and women. The financial material detail operating expenses, membership dues, payroll and miscellaneous accounts.
